  "local_port": 57266,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Can risotto be made using a rice cooker?",
  "response": "Yes, risotto can be made using a rice cooker, although traditionalists might argue that the classic stovetop method yields a better texture and flavor. However, using a rice cooker can be a convenient and hands-off way to make risotto. Here's a basic method to make risotto in a rice cooker:\n\n### Ingredients:\n- 1 1/2 cups Arborio rice\n- 4 cups chicken or vegetable broth\n- 1 small onion, finely chopped\n- 2 cloves garlic, minced\n- 1/2 cup white wine (optional)\n- 1/2 cup grated Parmesan cheese\n- 2 tablespoons butter\n- Salt and pepper to taste\n- Optional add-ins: mushrooms, peas, shrimp, etc.\n\n### Instructions:\n\n1. **Prep the Ingredients:**\n   - Heat the broth in a saucepan until warm, then set aside.\n   - In a skillet, saut\u00e9 the chopped onion and garlic in a bit of butter or olive oil until softened and translucent.\n\n2. **Combine in Rice Cooker:**\n   - Transfer the saut\u00e9ed onion and garlic to the rice cooker.\n   - Add the Arborio rice and stir to coat the rice with the onion mixture.\n   - If using white wine, pour it in and stir to combine.\n\n3. **Add Broth:**\n   - Pour the warm broth into the rice cooker. Stir everything together to ensure the rice is evenly distributed.\n\n4. **Cook:**\n   - Close the lid and set the rice cooker to the \"cook\" or \"white rice\" setting. Let it cook until the cycle is complete. This usually takes about 20-30 minutes, but timing can vary depending on your rice cooker.\n\n5. **Stir and Finish:**\n   - Once the rice cooker switches to the \"warm\" setting, open the lid and stir the risotto. It should be creamy but still have a bit of bite (al dente).\n   - Stir in the grated Parmesan cheese and additional butter. Season with salt and pepper to taste.\n   - If using any optional add-ins like cooked mushrooms, peas, or shrimp, stir them in at this point.\n\n6. **Serve:**\n   - Let the risotto sit for a few minutes to allow the flavors to meld, then serve hot.\n\n### Tips:\n- **Stirring:** While the rice cooker does most of the work, you can stir the risotto a couple of times during cooking to ensure even cooking and creaminess.\n- **Consistency:** If the risotto is too thick, you can stir in a bit more warm broth to achieve the desired consistency.\n- **Variations:** Feel free to experiment with different flavors and add-ins to customize your risotto.\n\nUsing a rice cooker to make risotto can save you time and effort, and the results can be quite delicious. Give it a try and see how it works for you!",
